            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "This syntax change does not appear to apply to pointers, correct? For example, the following code works fine.\r\n```python\r\ncdef char[4] char_array\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut this does not work (produces \"Syntax error in C variable declaration\"),\r\n```python\r\ncdef char*[4] char_ptr_array\r\n```\r\n\r\nChanging it to the c-declaration style does work.\r\n```python\r\ncdef char* char_ptr_array[4]\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe documentation states that, \"C-style array declarations (`cdef int a[4]`) are now (silently) deprecated in favour of the Java-style `cdef int[4] a` form.\" \r\n\r\nSo, will `cdef char*[4] char_ptr_array` be allowed in the future. More importantly, will a hard deprecation block `cdef char* char_ptr_array[4]` soon?\r\n\r\nRunning Cython 3.0.4\r\n\r\n",
